# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Because the leading transcendentalists began to focus their efforts on eliminating chattel slavery, transcendentalism faded from the scene by the 1850s. The ideas and writings of the transcendentalists, however, continued to inspire later reform movements, including the movement for [women's suffrage](/humanities/ap-us-history/period-4/apush-culture-and-reform/a/womens-rights-and-the-seneca-falls-convention), and the [labor movement](/humanities/ap-us-history/period-6/apush-gilded-age/a/labor-battles-in-the-gilded-age)."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-4/apush-culture-and-reform/a/transcendentalism">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-4/apush-culture-and-reform/a/transcendentalism</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Other influential transcendentalists were feminist pioneers. **Margaret Fuller**, a journalist and women’s rights advocate, edited *The Dial*, which was first published in 1840 and served as the primary journal of the transcendentalists until 1844. She was a frequent contributor to the journal and in 1845 published *Woman in the Nineteenth Century*, an early feminist manifesto that may have inspired the 1848 [Seneca Falls Convention](/humanities/ap-us-history/period-4/apush-culture-and-reform/a/womens-rights-and-the-seneca-falls-convention)—the first conference in America devoted to the issue of women’s rights.$^4$"
