# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "The Barbary Pirates weren’t the only source of trouble on the high seas for US ships during Jefferson’s presidency. France and England were engaged in the [Napoleonic Wars](/humanities/world-history/1600s-1800s/napoleon-bonaparte/v/french-revolution-part-4-the-rise-of-napoleon-bonaparte), which raged between 1803 and 1815. As a result, both countries began to seize American ships. The British Royal Navy **impressed** American sailors, kidnapping them from US ships and forcing them to serve in the British navy. The issue came to a head in 1807 when the HMS Leopard, a British warship, fired on a US ship, the Chesapeake, off the coast of Norfolk, Virginia. The British then boarded the ship and took four sailors. "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-4/apush-politics-society-early-19th-c/a/thomas-jefferson-as-president">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-4/apush-politics-society-early-19th-c/a/thomas-jefferson-as-president</a>.
