#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "After the demise of the Federalist Party, the second party system took hold, dividing the nation into two parties: the new Democratic Party and the Whig Party. The parties disagreed mainly about economic policy. Whigs advocated for accelerated economic growth, often endorsing federal government projects to achieve that goal. Democrats wanted the federal government to play a smaller role in regulating the economy. Whigs tended to be wealthier; they were prominent planters in the South and wealthy urban northerners--in other words, the beneficiaries of the market revolution. Democrats presented themselves as defenders of the common people against the elite. "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-5/apush-sectional-tension-1850s/a/the-kansas-nebraska-act">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-5/apush-sectional-tension-1850s/a/the-kansas-nebraska-act</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "As a result, the **Republican Party** became a solidly northern political organization, creating a new binary party system reflecting sectional fault lines along the question of slavery."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-5/apush-sectional-tension-1850s/a/the-kansas-nebraska-act">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-5/apush-sectional-tension-1850s/a/the-kansas-nebraska-act</a>.
