#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "In 1840, the abolitionist movement entered the contest for political office, catalyzing the shift away from the second party system. Members of the movement established the **Liberty Party** and nominated James G. Birney—a former slaveholder turned antislavery activist—as its candidate for president. Though Birney garnered only a tiny percentage of votes, his candidacy drew national attention to the abolitionist movement. Birney ran again in 1844 and received nearly ten times as many votes as he had in 1840. In 1848, the newly-formed **Free Soil Party** nominated former president Martin Van Buren and ran on an antislavery platform of “Free Soil, Free Labor, Free Men.”"
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-5/apush-sectional-tension-1850s/a/the-kansas-nebraska-act">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-5/apush-sectional-tension-1850s/a/the-kansas-nebraska-act</a>.
