# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "* President Truman authorized the use of the atom bombs in an effort to bring about Japan’s surrender in the **Second World War**. In the days following the bombings Japan surrendered. "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-7/apush-us-wwii/a/the-manhattan-project-and-the-atomic-bomb">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-7/apush-us-wwii/a/the-manhattan-project-and-the-atomic-bomb</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "* The **Manhattan Project** was the US government program during World War II that developed and built these first atomic bombs."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-7/apush-us-wwii/a/the-manhattan-project-and-the-atomic-bomb">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-7/apush-us-wwii/a/the-manhattan-project-and-the-atomic-bomb</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "* The United States detonated two atomic bombs over the Japanese cities of **Hiroshima** and **Nagasaki** in August 1945, killing 210,000 people—children, women, and men. "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-7/apush-us-wwii/a/the-manhattan-project-and-the-atomic-bomb">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-7/apush-us-wwii/a/the-manhattan-project-and-the-atomic-bomb</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "On August 6, 1945 an American B-29 bomber named the “**Enola Gay**” dropped the first atomic bomb on the city of **Hiroshima**. The device exploded over the city with a force of 12,500 tons of TNT. “[The city] had been there just a few minutes before . . . but it was absolutely gone,” said one witness. About 140,000 people were killed instantly or died  due to injury or radiation poisoning within months of the blast at Hiroshima.$^3$"
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-7/apush-us-wwii/a/the-manhattan-project-and-the-atomic-bomb">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-7/apush-us-wwii/a/the-manhattan-project-and-the-atomic-bomb</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Truman called for surrender the day after the bombing at Hiroshima once more, but once more the Japanese government refused. On August 9, about 80,000 people died after the United States dropped a second bomb on the Japanese city of **Nagasaki**. A total of 210,000 civilians died in the two atomic blasts. (In comparison, the United States had killed 120,000 Japanese civilians with conventional bombs during air raids on Tokyo in March 1945.)$^4$"
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-7/apush-us-wwii/a/the-united-nations">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-7/apush-us-wwii/a/the-united-nations</a>.
