# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "* Following **World War II**, the United States experienced a greatly elevated birth rate, adding on average 4.24 million new babies to the population every year between 1946 and 1964."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-baby-boom">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-baby-boom</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "* This generation of **\"baby boomers\"** was the result of a strong postwar economy, in which Americans felt confident they would be able to support a larger number of children. Boomers also influenced the economy as a core marketing demographic for products tied to their age group, from toys to records.  "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-baby-boom">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-baby-boom</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "As they age, the ratio of retired Americans compared to working Americans will increase significantly, placing considerable strain on Social Security, hospitals, and other government agencies designed to aid the elderly. The Census Bureau estimates that by 2030 one in five Americans will be over the age of 65. Furthermore, as the US birth rate is currently at an all-time low of just 12.5 live births per thousand population, by 2056 Americans aged 65 or older will outnumber those under the age of 18.$^{11}$ What effect this aging population will have on US society remains to be seen."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-baby-boom">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-baby-boom</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Historians and demographers have pointed out a number of possible reasons for this increased devotion to domesticity and child-rearing after the war, from government propaganda extolling the virtues of apple-pie American life during the war to a yearning for the security offered by \"normal\" family life during an era when fear of the atomic bomb pervaded society. One thing is certain: these high fertility rates closely correlate with a period of unprecedented economic prosperity, as well as optimism that the prosperity would last. After years of barely getting by during the **Great Depression** and enduring shortages and rationing during the war, Americans finally could afford to have a lot of children, so they did.$^7$ "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-baby-boom">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-baby-boom</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
