#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Start of the Cold War - The Yalta Conference and containment"
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-cold-war-part-1">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-cold-war-part-1</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "* The \"third world\" referred to everywhere else, usually developing countries in Asia and Latin America over which the United States and Soviet Union vied for influence"
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-cold-war-part-1">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-cold-war-part-1</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "* The US ambassador in Moscow warned that the Soviet Union desired to expand throughout the world and prescribed the **\"containment\"** of communism as the chief US foreign policy strategy."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-cold-war-part-1">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-cold-war-part-1</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid ""
"Amid this tense atmosphere, the US government received dire intelligence from its ambassador in Moscow, George F. Kennan.\n"
"In a **Long Telegram** sent to the US Secretary of State in 1946, Kennan warned that the Soviets believed that \"there could be no peaceful coexistence\" between communists and capitalists, and that the Soviets desired the relentless expansion not only of their own borders but of communism writ large.$^4$"
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-cold-war-part-1">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-cold-war-part-1</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "As the war moved into its final stages in mid-1945, suspicion flared between the United States and the Soviet Union. The terrifying new power of the atomic bomb, which the United States dropped on Japan in August, made the Soviets justifiably nervous. The United States also didn't endear itself to Russia when it abruptly cut off all military and financial aid to the Soviet Union upon the war's conclusion, at a time when Russian citizens dearly needed the help. For its part, the Soviet Union was sending clear signals that it did not intend to give up the territory it had gained from the Nazis, including stalling on its promises to remove troops from oil-rich regions in the Middle East and to allow free elections in conquered Poland.$^3$"
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-cold-war-part-1">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-cold-war-part-1</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Is \"Cold War\" really an appropriate name for the conflict between the United States and the Soviet Union? In what ways was the Cold War actually a hot war? "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-cold-war-part-1">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-cold-war-part-1</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "The US government adopted Kennan's ideas for containment, which became the cornerstone of American foreign policy in the twentieth century.$^5$"
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-cold-war-part-1">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-cold-war-part-1</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "The United States and USSR clashed over their economic and political philosophies. As a capitalist, democratic nation, the US sought to promote free elections and free markets. As a communist, totalitarian state, the USSR sought to ensure the security of its borders and the political dominance of the Communist party."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-dark-side-of-suburbia">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-dark-side-of-suburbia</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "But this conformity also had a dark side. For white women, the charms of suburban life began to wear thin after a few years. Although it should not be forgotten that more than 30% of women did work outside the home in some capacity during the 1950s, popular culture was replete with messages counseling women that their greatest satisfaction in life would come from raising children, tending to their husbands' needs, and owning all of the labor-saving household appliances that money could buy. But many began to identify a creeping sense that there ought to be more to life than childcare and housework.$^4$"
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-dark-side-of-suburbia">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-dark-side-of-suburbia</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Levitt and Sons went on to build two more highly-successful suburbs in Pennsylvania and New Jersey (both of which they also named Levittown), and other developers quickly adopted their formula for suburban housing. Between 1948 and 1958, 85% of the new homes built in the United States were located in suburbs. Suburban construction across the country also meant that regional differences of architecture and urban planning began to erode in favor of identical housing across the United States. This suburban trend has endured: today, four out of five Americans live in suburbs.$^1$"
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-dark-side-of-suburbia">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-dark-side-of-suburbia</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "The war and its aftermath also changed American living patterns on a large scale. Defense plants in the southern and western United States drew workers during the war, and in the following decades more Americans moved to the warmer states of the **Sunbelt** in search of jobs. The population of California doubled between 1940 and 1960. Florida's population nearly tripled in the same period. In general, people, jobs, and money began to move away from the industrial states of the Northeast and the Upper Midwest and into the South and West.$^2$"
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-gi-bill">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-gi-bill</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid " Hoping to provide servicemen and women with a measure of financial security upon their return (and, hopefully, siphon a substantial proportion of veterans away from the labor market and into educational programs), President Franklin D. Roosevelt signed the **Servicemen's Readjustment Act** on June 22, 1944. Commonly known as the **GI Bill**, the Servicemen's Readjustment Act offered veterans a year of unemployment pay after their homecoming; guaranties for loans to purchase homes, businesses, or farms; and tuition and living stipends for college or vocational programs. "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-gi-bill">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-gi-bill</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "* Enacted by Congress in 1944, the **GI Bill** sent more than eight million World War II veterans to school between 1945 and 1956. "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-gi-bill">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-gi-bill</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "1) **Educational support.** Veterans were entitled to \\$500 per year toward tuition and as well as a living stipend of \\$65-90 per month depending on whether the veteran had a family to support during his or her schooling. "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-gi-bill">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-gi-bill</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "But this judgment proved premature. The GI Bill was an unprecedented success, sending eight million veterans to school in the decade after World War II and completely reinventing American higher education. Despite the hefty price tag of the program  - about \\$14.5 billion dollars - veterans who took advantage of the educational subsidy earned, on average, \\$10,000-15,000 more per year than those who did not, generating ten times the cost of the program in tax revenue. Consequently, some analysts have called it \"the best investment  the US government has ever made.\"$^2$"
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-gi-bill">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-gi-bill</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "How was the passage of the GI Bill related to the rise of America suburbia? "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-gi-bill">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-gi-bill</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Imagine you were returning from World War II. Which of the GI Bill benefits do you think would be most important to you and why?"
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-gi-bill">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-gi-bill</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "In 1944, FDR was running for reelection, seeking an unprecedented fourth term as president of the United States. During the [Great Depression](/humanities/ap-us-history/period-7/apush-great-depression/a/the-great-depression), he had won broad popular support through the [New Deal](/humanities/ap-us-history/period-7/apush-great-depression/a/the-new-deal), which sought to use government programs to ensure baseline economic security for the American people. During his State of the Union address in 1944, Roosevelt proposed a radical \"economic bill of rights\" that would guarantee American citizens employment, health care, education, and housing.$^3$ In the midst of the wartime economic boom, however, this promise of security failed to animate voters as it had a decade earlier. "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-gi-bill">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-gi-bill</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Not everyone greeted this plan with enthusiasm. Accustomed to a pre-war society where college education was reserved for the elite, the president of the University of Chicago griped that \"Education is not a device for coping with mass unemployment . . . colleges and universities will find themselves converted into educational hobo jungles.\"$^1$ "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-gi-bill">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-gi-bill</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "The US government was anxious, too, but for a different reason. World War II had revived American prosperity after more than a decade of depression, and the government was desperate to fend off the economic turmoil that 15 million veterans reentering the workforce might wreak."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-gi-bill">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-gi-bill</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "The government guaranty for home and business loans also prompted an economic boom, financing the construction of thousands of new homes, like those that sprang up in [suburbs](/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-growth-of-suburbia) such as Levittown, New York. "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-gi-bill">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-gi-bill</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid ""
"This bill, which I have signed today, substantially carries out most of the recommendations made by me in a speech on July 28, 1943, and more specifically in messages to the Congress dated October 27, 1943, and November 23, 1943:\n"
"It gives servicemen and women the opportunity of resuming their education or technical training after discharge, or of taking a refresher or retrainer course, not only without tuition charge up to \\$500 per school year, but with the right to receive a monthly living allowance while pursuing their studies."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-gi-bill">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-gi-bill</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Why do historians believe the GI Bill to be so transformative in American education?"
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-growth-of-suburbia">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-growth-of-suburbia</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "* In the postwar era, many Americans moved away from cities and into suburbs, helped by **GI Bill** benefits that guarantied home loans. "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-growth-of-suburbia">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-growth-of-suburbia</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Portions of this article were adapted from  [\"The American Dream\"](http://cnx.org/contents/a7ba2fb8-8925-4987-b182-5f4429d48daa@3.150) article, OpenStax College, US History. OpenStax CNX. May 15, 2015."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-growth-of-suburbia">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/a/the-growth-of-suburbia</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "The American Dream: 2.5 kids, a dog, and a house with a white-picket fence. It's one of the most iconic and enduring images in American culture, the object of both praise (as evidence of a high standard of living) and ridicule (as evidence of conformity and materialism). The cookie-cutter homes that sprang up outside metropolitan areas after [World War II](/humanities/world-history/euro-hist/wo/v/beginning-of-world-war-ii) weren't grand palaces, but to the generation that had survived the  [Great Depression](humanities/ap-us-history/period-7/apush-great-depression/a/the-great-depression) and World War II these little cottages represented almost unimaginable luxury.  "
msgstr ""

