#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Ronald Reagan: Foreign policy"
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1980s-america/a/ronald-reagan-as-president-part-2-foreign-policy">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1980s-america/a/ronald-reagan-as-president-part-2-foreign-policy</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "* Despite Reagan's strong stance against communism, US-Soviet relations warmed during Reagan’s second term. In 1987 Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev signed the first-ever nuclear arms reduction treaty. By the end of Reagan's second term the **Cold War** was coming to an end. "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1980s-america/a/ronald-reagan-as-president-part-2-foreign-policy">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1980s-america/a/ronald-reagan-as-president-part-2-foreign-policy</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "* President Reagan’s second term was roiled by the **Iran-Contra affair**, in which the Reagan administration secretly sold weapons to Iran and used money from the sale to covertly fund the Contras, a group opposed to the government of Nicaragua."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1980s-america/a/ronald-reagan-as-president-part-2-foreign-policy">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1980s-america/a/ronald-reagan-as-president-part-2-foreign-policy</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "* Reagan's administration funded anti-communist “**freedom fighters**” in Afghanistan, Angola, Nicaragua, and elsewhere in order to effect a rollback of worldwide communist influence.  "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1980s-america/a/ronald-reagan-as-president-part-2-foreign-policy">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1980s-america/a/ronald-reagan-as-president-part-2-foreign-policy</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Full text of Reagan's \"[Evil Empire](https://reaganlibrary.archives.gov/archives/speeches/1983/30883b.htm)\" speech courtesy the Reagan Library."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1980s-america/a/ronald-reagan-as-president-part-2-foreign-policy">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1980s-america/a/ronald-reagan-as-president-part-2-foreign-policy</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "President Reagan’s second term was sullied by the [Iran-Contra affair](/humanities/us-history/modern-us/1980s-america/a/iran-contra), in which US officials secretly sold weapons to Iran and funneled the profits from those sales to Nicaraguan rebels. "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1980s-america/a/ronald-reagan-as-president-part-2-foreign-policy">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1980s-america/a/ronald-reagan-as-president-part-2-foreign-policy</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Seeking to contain and rollback Soviet communist influence around the world, President Reagan’s administration funded anti-communist “freedom fighters” around the world, sending covert aid to anti-communist UNITA rebels in Angola; covert military support to the Contras seeking to overthrow the Marxist government of Nicaragua; and authorized aid to the mujahideen in Afghanistan in their battle against the Soviet Union.$^2$ "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1990s-america/a/bill-clinton-as-president">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1990s-america/a/bill-clinton-as-president</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "* Despite **the Lewinsky affair**, Clinton left the White House with the highest approval rating of any US president in the post-World War II era."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1990s-america/a/globalization">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1990s-america/a/globalization</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "With the collapse of the Soviet Union in 1989 and the end of the [Cold War](/humanities/ap-us-history/period-8/apush-postwar-era/v/origins-of-the-cold-war) in 1991, the world became more interconnected. This is because the communist bloc countries, which had previously been intentionally isolated from the capitalist West, began to integrate into the global market economy. Trade and investment increased, while barriers to migration and to cultural exchange were lowered."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1990s-america/a/the-election-of-2000">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1990s-america/a/the-election-of-2000</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "* The 2000 presidential election pitted Republican **George W. Bush** against Democrat **Al Gore**."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1990s-america/a/the-election-of-2000">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1990s-america/a/the-election-of-2000</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "* The outcome of the election was ultimately decided by the US Supreme Court in ***Bush v. Gore***. The court, in a 5-4 vote, ruled in favor of Bush."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1990s-america/a/the-election-of-2000">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1990s-america/a/the-election-of-2000</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "In the resulting case, ***Bush v. Gore***, the US Supreme Court ordered that the recount be stopped. The incomplete recount was halted, and Bush was awarded Florida’s electoral votes and declared the president-elect.$^1$"
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1990s-america/a/the-election-of-2000">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1990s-america/a/the-election-of-2000</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "The Supreme Court decision in *Bush v. Gore* was controversial because the 5-4 vote was along partisan lines, meaning the justices appointed by Republican presidents (with the exception of Justice David Souter) ruled in favor of Bush, and the justices appointed by Democratic presidents argued in favor of Gore. Another point of controversy in the 2000 election was the fact that George W. Bush’s brother, Jeb Bush, was the governor of Florida at the time of the recount,  although no evidence of wrongdoing surfaced. Al Gore conceded the election to Bush, but disagreed with the US Supreme Court’s ruling.$^2$"
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1990s-america/a/the-gulf-war">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1990s-america/a/the-gulf-war</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "* At the end of February, Hussein signed a cease-fire agreement and released Kuwait. After the war, Iraq was required to submit to inspections to ensure it possessed no chemical or other **weapons of mass destruction**."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1990s-america/a/the-gulf-war">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1990s-america/a/the-gulf-war</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "* In response, the United States and the UN Security Council demanded that Iraqi dictator **Saddam Hussein** withdraw Iraqi troops from Kuwait, but Hussein refused. "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1990s-america/a/the-gulf-war">http://translate.khanacademy.org/humanities/ap-us-history/period-9/apush-1990s-america/a/the-gulf-war</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: de)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "* Over the course of six weeks in January and February 1991, a United States-led coalition of 34 nations began an intensive bombing campaign against strategic Iraqi locations, culminating with a four-day ground campaign against Iraqi forces known as **Operation Desert Storm**.  "
msgstr ""

